          <aside class="ux">
            <h3>Target Users:</h3>
            <p>
              Gesture Researchers. Specifically gesture researchers who uses Microsoft X-Box Kinect as a part of their researches.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <aside class="code">
            <h3>MAIN TOOLS:</h3>
            <p>
              Node.js | MongoDB | Mustache | Passport | D3.js | x3dom | HTML | Bootstrap | Github | Heroku
            </p>
          </aside>
          <aside class="ux code">
            <h3>Challenge:</h3>
            <p>
              Existing Kinect data analyzing programs such as <a href="https://tla.mpi.nl/tools/tla-tools/elan/" target="_blank" class="no-ajaxy">ELAN</a> and <a href="http://chronoviz.com/" target="_blank" class="no-ajaxy">ChronoViz</a> have limitations on the visualization. Gesture researchers do not have the ability to change its size and dimension, and most importantly, they do not have the freedom to manipulate the visualization. Some researchers even filtered data points by omitting the z coordinate, so that they can create their own 2D visualization. These limitations and work-around pose a critical constrain on the full potential of the Kinect data.
            </p>
            <h3>Idea:</h3>
            <p>
              Overall, the user data suggested that these programs' design has violated the user experience by restricting the users' freedom and control. Therefore, a more manipulative visualization is much needed for their researches.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <aside class="ux code">
            <figure>
